body18 = (
    h2("What Is an Attorney Knowledge Panel?") +
    p("An attorney Knowledge Panel is the information box that appears on the right side of Google search results when someone searches for an attorney by name. It typically displays the attorney's photo, name, title and firm, a brief biography, contact information, social media profiles, notable cases or awards, bar admission information, and links to their firm website and major directory profiles. A Knowledge Panel signals that Google's knowledge graph has sufficient information to confidently identify and describe this attorney as a recognized professional entity.") +
    p("Attorney Knowledge Panels are significant for several reasons. For potential clients searching for a specific attorney — perhaps after a referral or after seeing the attorney's name in a news article — a Knowledge Panel provides immediate credibility signals: this is a real, established attorney with a documented professional history. For AI search systems, the existence of an attorney Knowledge Panel is a strong signal that the attorney is a recognized entity worth citing in responses to queries about legal professionals in their practice area.") +
    p("Not all attorneys have Knowledge Panels. Google generates them automatically for attorneys whose entity data meets a threshold of completeness, consistency, and third-party validation. Building toward an attorney Knowledge Panel is therefore a core component of entity SEO for individual attorneys — and by extension, for the law firms they work at, since an attorney with a strong entity record strengthens the firm's entity record as well.") +
    callout("Attorneys with Google Knowledge Panels are cited in AI-generated responses to legal professional queries at approximately 4x the rate of attorneys without Knowledge Panels, because the Knowledge Panel itself is evidence of recognized entity status in Google's knowledge graph.") +

    h2("What Google Needs to Generate an Attorney Knowledge Panel") +
    p("Google generates Knowledge Panels when its systems can confidently identify a person or organization as a distinct, notable entity with sufficient supporting data from multiple authoritative sources. For attorneys, the threshold of notability is lower than for public figures like politicians or celebrities — attorneys with sufficient professional documentation and online presence can earn Knowledge Panels without being nationally famous.") +
    p("The key inputs to attorney Knowledge Panel generation are: the state bar record (which provides an authoritative, government-validated confirmation of the attorney's existence, bar number, admission date, and practice status), legal directory profiles (Avvo, Martindale-Hubbell, Super Lawyers, FindLaw — each providing additional confirmation and detail), the attorney's bio page on their firm website with Person schema markup, social media profiles (particularly LinkedIn), any press mentions or publications, and any awards or recognition from legal industry organizations.") +
    p("The combination of state bar record + major directory profiles + firm bio with schema + LinkedIn is usually sufficient to trigger Knowledge Panel generation for attorneys in markets where such panels are regularly appearing. Attorneys in niche practice areas, smaller markets, or newer practices may need to build more third-party validation before Google's confidence threshold is met. The process is not instantaneous — Google's systems need to index, process, and synthesize information from multiple sources over time.") +

    h2("Optimizing State Bar and Directory Profiles") +
    p("The state bar record is the most authoritative data source for attorney entity information. Ensure your state bar profile is accurate and complete: correct name (in the exact form you want associated with your entity), current contact information, correct admission date and bar number, and any specialization certifications your bar offers. If your state bar provides optional additional fields — firm affiliation, practice areas, biographical information — complete them. This authoritative data feeds directly into knowledge graph construction.") +
    p("Avvo is typically the most important legal directory for attorney Knowledge Panel purposes because of its scale, its structured attorney data, and its authority signals. Claim your Avvo profile, upload a professional headshot, complete your education and employment history, list your practice areas with specificity (not just 'Litigation' but 'Personal Injury Litigation,' 'Premises Liability,' 'Motor Vehicle Accidents'), and request peer endorsements from colleagues and former clients reviews from satisfied clients. An Avvo Rating of 10 and a complete profile with peer endorsements is a significant entity authority signal.") +
    p("Martindale-Hubbell is the oldest and in many respects most prestigious legal directory. Peer Review Ratings from Martindale-Hubbell — AV Preeminent (the highest), BV Distinguished, or plain Listed — carry significant weight as third-party credibility signals because they represent genuine peer evaluation by fellow attorneys and judges. If you have not applied for a Martindale-Hubbell Peer Review Rating, it is worth initiating the process — the credential itself, separate from its directory listing value, is a meaningful entity authority signal.") +

    h2("Building Your Firm Bio Page for Knowledge Panel Impact") +
    p("Your attorney bio page on your firm's website is one of the most directly controllable inputs to your Knowledge Panel development. A rich, well-structured bio page with proper Person schema markup provides Google with explicit structured data about your attorney identity that can feed directly into knowledge graph construction and Knowledge Panel generation.") +
    p("An optimized attorney bio page includes: a professional headshot (consistent with the photo in your directory profiles), full professional name, current title and firm affiliation, bar admission information (state, year, bar number if public), law school and graduation year, undergraduate institution, areas of practice (listed specifically), professional recognitions and awards, bar association memberships and leadership roles, publications and speaking engagements, and a substantive 3-5 paragraph biography that covers career arc, expertise, and personal professional philosophy.") +
    p("The biography content should be written specifically for the bio page and not duplicated from any other profile. Unique content signals to Google that this page is the authoritative source for this attorney's professional information, rather than a copy of information found elsewhere. Include specific details about cases, clients (anonymously where required), jurisdictions, and outcomes that demonstrate genuine expertise — this depth of content supports E-E-A-T signals that Google weighs heavily for legal professional profiles.") +

    h2("LinkedIn: The Social Entity Signal for Attorneys") +
    p("LinkedIn is the most important social platform for attorney Knowledge Panel development because it is a recognized, high-authority source of professional information that Google's knowledge graph actively indexes and incorporates. A complete, accurate LinkedIn profile for an attorney provides an additional authoritative confirmation of their professional identity that strengthens their entity record.") +
    p("An optimized LinkedIn profile for an attorney includes: a professional headshot consistent with other profiles, the attorney's full name and current firm in the headline, complete education history (law school, undergrad, any LLM or specialized degrees), complete employment history with dates, a skills section that lists legal specializations, endorsements from colleagues for specific skills, a substantial 'About' section covering professional background and expertise, any publications or articles authored, and links to their firm website and notable case or publication references.") +
    p("LinkedIn activity — publishing articles, sharing legal insights, commenting on legal developments in the news — provides additional signals that the attorney is an active professional rather than an historical record. While LinkedIn activity is not a direct Knowledge Panel ranking factor, it contributes to the overall entity signal strength by demonstrating that the attorney maintains a current, active professional presence on a major professional platform.") +

    h2("Media Mentions and Publications as Entity Validators") +
    p("Third-party media mentions are among the most powerful entity validation signals because they represent independent confirmation of an attorney's existence, expertise, and professional standing by sources that have no incentive to create false records. When a local newspaper quotes your attorney as a legal expert, when a legal blog publishes an article you authored, when a bar association newsletter features your commentary on a new legal development — each of these creates an authoritative third-party mention that feeds into your entity record.") +
    p("Building a strategy for earning media mentions starts with positioning your attorneys as available expert sources for journalists covering legal topics. Identify the reporters and editors at local media outlets who cover courts, crime, business, and family matters. Send a brief introduction email with your areas of expertise and an offer to be available for expert commentary on legal matters in your specialty. When major legal news breaks in your practice area, proactively reach out with timely, useful commentary.") +
    p("Publishing articles in legal publications — bar association journals, legal blogs, practitioner-focused magazines — is another high-value media mention strategy. Authored articles establish intellectual authority and create permanent, authoritative records of your expertise that feed into your entity record. Even state and local bar association newsletter contributions count — the bar association is itself a highly authoritative entity, and content published by it carries significant third-party validation weight.") +

    h2("Monitoring and Maintaining Your Knowledge Panel") +
    p("Once your attorney Knowledge Panel appears, monitoring it regularly ensures that the information displayed is accurate and up to date. Knowledge Panels can occasionally display incorrect information — a wrong phone number, an outdated firm affiliation, a photo you did not intend to be featured — and correcting these inaccuracies requires using Google's feedback mechanism.") +
    p("To suggest corrections to your Knowledge Panel, click the 'Claim this knowledge panel' or 'Suggest an edit' button at the bottom of the panel. This initiates a verification process that links the Knowledge Panel to your Google account, after which you can suggest corrections and Google will review them. Verified panel owners can also update certain information directly. If you cannot find these options, the 'Feedback' button at the bottom of the panel allows you to flag specific inaccuracies for Google's review team.") +
    p("Regularly search for your own name to monitor your Knowledge Panel's appearance and content. If your firm affiliation changes, if you earn a new award or certification, or if any other panel information becomes outdated, address it promptly. A Knowledge Panel with outdated or inaccurate information can actually work against you if it creates contradictions with your current online presence — accuracy is as important as existence when it comes to entity authority.")
)

